  "prompt": "Will people still be able to have websites with no net neutrality?",
  "response": "Yes, people will still be able to have websites even if net neutrality is not enforced, but the experience might be different. Net neutrality is the principle that Internet service providers (ISPs) should treat all data on the Internet the same, not discriminating or charging differently by user, content, website, or platform. Without net neutrality, ISPs have the ability to prioritize certain websites or services over others, potentially leading to slower access to some sites and faster access to others based on commercial agreements or their own interests.\n\nHere are some potential impacts of a lack of net neutrality:\n1. **Tiered Services**: ISPs may offer tiered services where websites or services that pay a premium can load faster, while others may be relegated to slower lanes.\n2. **Blocking or Throttling**: ISPs might block or throttle content from competitors or content providers that do not pay extra fees.\n3. **Increased Costs**: Smaller websites and startups might face higher costs if they need to pay ISPs to ensure fast delivery of their content, potentially stifling innovation and competition.\n\nDespite these potential challenges, individuals and businesses will still be able to create and maintain websites. The key difference will be how accessible their content is to users and whether they can afford to pay for better service levels from ISPs.",
